Fig. 2
 displays the actual data against the predicted values of PCE. The result shows good model predictability due to the reduced quadratic model fits the experimental data. Graphs of surface response against each independent parameter were plotted (Fig. 3
) to study the effect of each parameter (concentration of TTIP, number of cycle and volume of GQD) towards the PCE. to study the. According to ANOVA, the model term A and C are significant towards the surface response because as the concentration of TTIP and volume of GQD are increased from 50 to 100 mM and 1 to 5.5 μL, respectively the PCE also increase drastically (Fig. 3a and Fig. 3c). However, further increasing the concentration of TTIP and volume of GQD up to 150 mM and 10 μL, respectively the PCE decrease drastically (Fig. 3a and Fig. 3c). According to ANOVA, the model term B is not significant towards the surface response and this statement can be justified in Fig. 3b. As the number of cycle increase from 1 to 2, the PCE increase but not drastically. Furthermore, increasing the number of cycles up to 3, the PCE does not drop drastically. The 3D surface plot depicts an intense curvature, demonstrating a strong interaction between the PCE and each independent parameter (Fig. 4a and b). As shown in Table 3, this result is parallel with the significant of the model term AB and model term AC.

The reduced quadratic model validation test and optimization of surface response were executed to measure the RSE and the low RSE value indicates the model is valid and possesses high accuracy to predict the surface response. All the independent parameters were set in the range and the PCE was set to the maximum value (Table 4
                        ). The Design-Expert software proposed three sets of experiments and the optimum parameters to produce TiO2-GQD LSL are recorded in Table 5
                        . The validation test exhibits RSE values of less than 3%, demonstrating the model is good and able to predict the surface response accurately up to 97%.
